    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-03-28T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-03-28T12:00:00-05:00" n="638"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d638">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.659 Matches/12: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-03-28T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 28, 1936—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>67. Nanking’s despatches Nos. 98<note n="21" xml:id="d638fn21">Not
                        printed.</note> and 103 of February 21 and 27 in regard to proposed match
                    monopoly. On the basis of the information contained in the Embassy’s despatches,
                    the Department is inclined to concur in the view expressed in the penultimate
                    paragraph of Nanking’s No. 98 under reference.<note n="22" xml:id="d638fn22">The
                        Ambassador in China stated that it was his intention “to take no further
                        step in connection with the discussions relating to the formation of a match
                        monopoly unless it shall seem necessary to emphasize further the opposition
                        of the American Government to monopolies.” (893.659 Matches/11)</note> In
                    this connection, the Embassy should bear in mind Department’s instruction No.
                    1745 of September 4, 1935,<note n="23" xml:id="d638fn23">
                        <ref target="frus1935v03#pg_786">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1935, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 786</ref>.</note> on the subject of
                    monopolies.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
